1. What does binding my device to an account do?
Binding an aircraft with an account means the account has ownership of the aircraft. If the bound account is changed, it means device ownership is transferred to the new account

2. What happens if the current account in use is not the aircraft owner's account?
A. You can use the current account to connect to and use the aircraft normally, but you will be unable to check device usage and other related information
B. You may be unable to use certain value-added services for the aircraft, such as DJI Care Flyaway Coverage included in DJI Care Enterprise Plus or DJI Care Pro
C. If the aircraft is designated as a flyaway aircraft by the aircraft owner's account, flying the aircraft is prohibited

3. Unbinding an aircraft from an account means anyone can connect to the aircraft and bind it to their account

1. DJI Care Flyaway Coverage is a service included in DJI Care Enterprise Plus or DJI Care Pro. If you lose your aircraft due to a flyaway incident and submit a DJI Care Flyaway Aircraft Report, you can receive a new aircraft after paying the service fee

2. What should I do to be able to use DJI Care Flyaway Coverage?
A. Bind the aircraft with your account in Device Management
B. Bind the aircraft with the remote controller in Device Management
C. After taking the above steps, DJI Care Flyaway Coverage can only be accessed using your bound account and remote controller

3. How do I use DJI Care Flyaway Coverage?
A. Go to the DJI official website and then go to Support > Online Repair Request and submit the flyaway incident information
B. Provide flight records for the flyaway aircraft to DJI to determine whether the flyaway aircraft incident meets the requirements for DJI Care Flyaway Coverage
C. Complete the DJI Care Flyaway Aircraft Report by following the instructions. After the report is confirmed, flying the aircraft is prohibited
D. Pay the DJI Care Flyaway Aircraft Coverage service fee
E. A replacement aircraft will be sent to you

1. What is a DJI Care Flyaway Aircraft Report?
Submitting a DJI Care Flyaway Aircraft Report designates your aircraft as lost due to a flyaway incident under DJI Care Flyaway Coverage. When the report is confirmed, flying the aircraft is prohibited. This operation is required to use DJI Care Flyaway Coverage.
If you haven't bound aircraft with remote controller when your aircraft flies away, you cannot complete the DJI Care Flyaway Aircraft Report. Check binding remote controller notes for details.
2. Can I cancel my submission after my report is confirmed?
If you haven't used your DJI Care Flyaway Coverage, you can contact DJI Support to cancel the submission and use the aircraft normally
If you have already used your DJI Care Flyaway Coverage, ownership of the lost aircraft is transferred to DJI, and you will be unable to cancel your submission
By tapping Next, you confirm that you agree with the above functions and risks that may occur

1. What does binding the remote controller do?
Binding the aircraft with the remote controller records the linking between the aircraft and the remote controller. If the aircraft is lost due to a flyaway incident, you can request to use DJI Care Flyaway Coverage included in DJI Care Enterprise Plus or DJI Care Pro. It is not possible to use DJI Care Flyaway Coverage if the aircraft is not bound with the remote controller

2. Can I change or unbind a bound remote controller?

After binding an aircraft with a remote controller, you must use the bound remote controller to control the aircraft. If you want to change or unbind the remote controller, connect the aircraft to the app and change or unbind the remote controller in Device Management

3. What information is collected when a remote controller is bound?

Information collected during binding includes the information for the bound DJI account, aircraft SN, remote controller SN, and remote controller device ID

4. Can I use the aircraft without network connection after binding aircraft with remote controller?

Yes. To provide you with better user experience, you can use the bound remote controller to fly the aircraft without connecting to the network

If any of the following gimbal issues occur, troubleshooting is required:
- Gimbal payload voltage too high
- Gimbal payload voltage too low
- Gimbal battery module overheated
- Gimbal battery module temperature too low
- Gimbal payload power too high
- Gimbal payload transmission error

Perform the following steps:
1. Reconnect the payload and check if any warning alerts are displayed.
2. If warning alerts are displayed, restart the aircraft and check again.
3. If the warning alerts persist, replace the payload with one in good working condition and check again. If warnings are not displayed for the replacement payload, the issue is a result of a payload malfunction. If warnings are still displayed for the replacement payload, then the issue may be with the connection port on the aircraft. Contact your local dealer or DJI Support.

If any of the following PSDK issues occur, troubleshooting is required:
- PSDK voltage too high
- PSDK voltage too low
- PSDK power too high

Perform the following steps:
1. Reconnect the PSDK module and check if warning alerts are displayed.
2. If warning alerts are displayed, restart the aircraft and check again.
3. If warning alerts are still displayed, replace the PSDK module with one in good working condition and check again. If no warning alerts are displayed, then the issue was caused by an PSDK device malfunction. If warnings alerts are still displayed for the replacement PSDK module, then the issue may be with the connection port on the aircraft. Contact your local dealer or DJI Support.

Battery maintenance required. Perform following steps to maintain battery:
1. Fully charge battery
2. Let battery sit for 24 hr
3. Insert battery into aircraft, take off, and let aircraft hover at a height up to 2 m. Contact your local dealer or DJI Support if aircraft cannot take off
4. When battery level drops to 20%, land, power off aircraft, and remove battery
5. Let battery sit for 6 hr
6. Repeat above steps if warning persists

1. Maximum speed and braking distance are increased significantly in Sport (S) mode. In windless conditions, a minimum braking distance of 50 meters is required.
2. Responsiveness is increased significantly in S mode. Minor stick movements on the remote controller will lead to large aircraft movements. Allow enough room for maneuvering based on the actual wind speed and conditions.
3. Descent speed is increased significantly in S mode. During high-speed descent, the downward vision system may not be able to brake in time. Allow enough room for braking.
4. Vision systems are disabled in S mode. The Aircraft will not automatically avoid obstacles or brake during flight. Always be alert and control the aircraft manually to avoid obstacles.

You are about to turn on the DJI Pilot app's data upload feature. DJI FlightHub is DJI's drone management platform, providing task, data, team, and equipment management services. These functions and services are based on data uploaded from the DJI Pilot app. After you turn on the DJI Pilot app's data upload feature, the following information will be uploaded to FlightHub: ● Information about your drone, including device ID, name, model, firmware version, language, and country. ● Your drone account username. ● Timestamp. ● Drone flight parameters, including takeoff time, current GNSS positioning information, and flight speed, altitude, direction, and duration. The livestream feature needs to be manually enabled, otherwise the livestream data will not be transferred to FlightHub. The above information is transferred and stored using the AWS service, and through the use of which you must comply with the User Agreement.

Authorization Zones are highlighted in blue on the map. When flying in an Authorization Zone, users will receive a warning alert and a message containing flight restrictions for the area. These zones can be unlocked by applying for an unlocking license. Temporary unlocking will expire after the aircraft is powered off.
Altitude Zones are highlighted in gray on the map. These areas have a flight altitude limit.
Airport Altitude Zones are highlighted in gray on the map. These areas have a flight altitude limit of 500m (1640ft).
Restricted Zones are highlighted in red on the map. Flight in these areas is prohibited. To obtain an unlocking license to fly in a Restricted Zone, contact flysafe@dji.com or unlock online.
Regulatory Restricted Zones are areas where flying is prohibited due to local regulations for special areas such as correctional facilities.

When flying in Enhanced Warning Zones, users will receive an alert from DJI GEO system asking them to apply for an unlocking license by following the same steps as unlocking Authorization Zones. Applying for an unlocking license for Enhanced Warning Zones does not require a real-name authenticated account.

Approved Zones for Light UAVs are highlighted in green on the map. These zones are pre-approved and recommended for flying. Pilots planning to fly light UAVs at an altitude of 120 m or less are not required to obtain permission to fly. Pilots who are planning to fly light UAVs in Approved Zones at an altitude higher than 120 m or in GEO Zones other than Approved Zones must obtain permission via UTMISS before taking off

When flying in Warning Zones, users will receive a warning alert notifying them of important information or restrictions for the zone in question. Certain Warning Zones may not be displayed on the map such as nature preserves.

Device Update includes checking for updates and downloading update packages for your DJI devices and DJI apps. Keeping your DJI devices and apps updated helps ensure optimal user experience. Enabling Device Update allows DJI Pilot to sync the following information for checking for updates and downloading update packages: account information, DJI devices firmware versions, and DJI apps versions.

DJI FlightHub 2 is a management platform. DJI Pilot syncs your account information, DJI device information, location information, aircraft attitude, flight speed, and real-time image transmission to DJI servers only when you are logged in to the FlightHub 2 Public Cloud team account. Syncing and sharing information with your team via DJI FlightHub 2 helps you and your team work more efficiently.

DJI cloud services include FlightHub 2, DeliveryHub, SmartFarm, and others. After logging in to corresponding platform, DJI Pilot 2 will sync your account and device information, location information, aircraft speed and attitude, and real-time image transmission data to platform. Using DJI cloud platforms to sync and share data with your team can improve teamwork efficiency

Sync Flight Records is a convenient tool for syncing DJI device flight records. DJI Pilot will sync your account information, DJI device serial numbers, location information, flight trajectory, flight speed, and sensor data to DJI servers only when you choose to upload them.
Authorize DJI to access and analyze flight records of your DJI account synchronized to DJI server. Such data will help us locate device issues and provide corresponding after-sales services

Fly Safe includes update checks and downloads for the Precise Fly Safe Database and unlocking license synchronization. It increases flight safety by providing more accurate GEO Zone information and is also a convenient and efficient way to unlock licenses from DJI. Enabling Fly Safe allows DJI Pilot to sync your DJI device information, the Precise Fly Safe Database version information, and fuzzy location information to DJI servers for GEO Zone database and temporary GEO Zone data updates. DJI Pilot only syncs your account information and DJI device serial number with DJI servers to unlock license when you use the license synchronization function.

Third-party cloud services support GB28181 protocol, RTMP, RTSP, and DJI IoT API. Only when you choose third-party cloud services will DJI Pilot sync DJI device serial numbers, location information, flight speed, real-time image transmission, aircraft attitude, camera attitude, sensor data, and livestream protocol to DJI servers

Sync Logs is a convenient tool for uploading DJI device logs. DJI Pilot will sync your account information and DJI device logs to DJI servers only when you choose to upload them. The logs contain various DJI device status information, including but not limited to, the DJI device serial number, flight trajectory, flight speed, and sensor data. This information will only be used to help DJI Support locate issues with the device.

Map service displays the location of mobile and DJI devices on the map in real time when aircraft is in flight. Enabling map service allows third-party map service providers to access location information of your mobile and DJI devices

Network RTK provides RTK data for your DJI devices from a third-party RTK service provider. Network RTK helps you use your DJI devices with more accurate positioning data. Third-party RTK service providers will gain access to your DJI devices\' location information only when you are using network RTK service. Your DJI devices\' location information will be used for requesting data from nearby RTK base stations.

Network RTK provides RTK data for your DJI devices from a third-party RTK service provider. Network RTK helps you use your DJI devices with more accurate positioning data. Third-party RTK service providers will gain access to your DJI devices\' location information only when you are using network RTK service. Your DJI devices\' location information will be used for requesting data from nearby RTK base stations. At the same time, DJI Pilot will report fuzzy location information of your devices and query the ionospheric activity level of nearby areas to evaluate the impact of ionospheric activity on RTK (Ionospheric activity query is only supported in the Chinese mainland)

DJI would like your help to improve the quality and performance of its products by collecting and sending device diagnostics and usage data. No DJI account details or personal information will be collected for this purpose.

According to the General Flight Rules of the People\'s Republic of China, the Regulations on the Control of General-Purpose Aviation Flight, and the Regulations on Real-time Flight Data for Light and Small Civilian UAVs, you are required to transmit data such as device info, GNSS positioning information, and flight data in real-time to the CAAC during flight. Make sure real-time flight data transmission is enabled for your aircraft.\nYour flight data will be transmitted to UTMISS of the CAAC through a real-time network connection or will be cached to your local device if the network connection does not work. The data will not be saved by or shared with any services supported by DJI. To learn more about which data is reported, refer to Regulations on Real-time Flight Data for Light and Small Civilian UAVs.

Welcome to the DJI Product Improvement Project. By participating in this project, you will share your data with DJI to help us improve our products and services.  DJI values your privacy and data collected through this project does not identify you personally. You may opt out of this project at any time through the \"Settings\" page. For more information, please see Privacy Policy. If you choose to participate in this project, the following information, to the extent applicable, will be collected and sent to DJI for analysis and product improvement purposes: - DJI hardware and software information, including product model, firmware version, device status, application version, and network information. - Diagnostic and usage data, including performance statistics, crash data, data about how you use your DJI device and the related application, usage frequency of DJI device, and application features.

After joining this project, you will share DJI device information, diagnostics, and usage data with DJI to help us improve DJI device performance and user experience.Before analyzing and using the data, we will desensitize and anonymize data based on industry security standards as needed to protect your privacy. Go to home screen > Data and Privacy > Network Security Mode to cancel the DJI Product Improvement Project at any time.

After changing to Relative to Takeoff Point (ALT), waypoint altitude during flight will be relative to takeoff point altitude
Different takeoff point altitudes will affect actual waypoint altitudes. Fly with caution
Waypoint altitude relative to takeoff point = Waypoint ellipsoidal height − Takeoff point ellipsoidal height Takeoff altitude in file will be regarded as ellipsoidal height. If there is no takeoff altitude data, takeoff altitude will be regarded as 0 m

After changing to ASL (EGM96), waypoint altitude during flight will be altitude above sea level (EGM96)
Waypoint altitude above sea level = Waypoint ellipsoidal height + Waypoint elevation anomaly Waypoint ellipsoidal height = Takeoff point ellipsoidal height + Waypoint altitude relative to takeoff point Takeoff altitude in file will be regarded as ellipsoidal height. If there is no takeoff altitude data, takeoff altitude will be regarded as 0 m
